@startuml

title WAL Direct I/O vs Page Cache

note as PageCacheChar #FFFFCC
**Page Cache**
• Kernel buffers writes in memory
• Good for general-purpose workloads
• Can have variable latency
• May add extra copies and cache pollution
• Write timing is less predictable
end note

note as DirectIOChar #E6FFE6
**Direct I/O**
• Bypasses the kernel page cache
• Fewer copies and less cache interference
• Better for large sequential WAL appends
• More predictable latency
• Usually needs alignment discipline
end note

note as AlignmentReqs #FFE6E6
**Direct I/O Requirements**
• Buffer address must be aligned
• Buffer size must be aligned
• File offset must be aligned
• The application must manage this complexity
end note

note as UsageGuidance #F0F8FF
**When to Use Each**

**Direct I/O is best for**
• Large sequential writes
• Predictable append-only WAL workloads
• Avoiding page cache pollution

**Page Cache is best for**
• Small random I/O
• Frequently re-read data
• Simpler application code
end note

note bottom #E6FFE6
**Key Insight**
WAL is often a great fit for Direct I/O because
it is append-heavy and values predictable latency.
end note

@enduml
